SIMPLE: inattention
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inattention
<hw>In`at*ten"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>attention</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>inattention</ets>.]</ety> <def>Lack of attention, or failure to pay
attention; disregard; heedlessness; neglect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Novel lays attract our ravished ears;⟦br⟧
But old, the mind <qex>inattention</qex> hears.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Inadvertence; heedlessness; negligence;
carelessness; disregard; remissness; thoughtlessness; neglect.</syn> --
<usage><er>Inattention</er>, <er>Inadvertence</er>. We miss seeing a
thing through <xex>inadvertence</xex> when <xex>do not happen to look
at</xex> it; through <xex>inattention</xex> when we <xex>give no heed
to</xex> it, though directly before us. The latter is therefore the
worse. <xex>Inadvertence</xex> may be an involuntary accident;
<xex>inattention</xex> is culpable neglect. A versatile mind is often
<xex>inadvertent</xex>; a careless or stupid one is
<xex>inattentive</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 742 --></p>

<p><ent>Inattentive</ent>⟦br⟧
